## Scope

This slice implements the curved-element domain model entirely within `OpticalConstructor.Domain` (`CurvedElements.fs`): the curved-surface geometry record, the spherical/aspheric figure DU and its sag function, the aperture decomposition into local flat zones, the per-zone local-AOI solver fan over the reused 4×4 solver, the beam-fan attachment onto the Part A `BeamTree`, inter-element propagation via the engine propagator, coating attachment as ordinary engine optical systems, and EUV depth-graded multilayer period scaling. It implements the §A.5 local-interface extension *contract* that slice 002 fixed.

There is no UI, no operator page, and no long-running job here (the operator-facing UX checklist does not apply per §C.0). This slice consumes — and MUST NOT redefine — the `BeamTree`/`BeamNode`/`BeamBranch`/`ConstructorElement` types owned by Part A §A.4 / slice 002, and reuses three engine seams unchanged: `OpticalSystemSolver`, `IncidentLightInfo.rotateY`, and `EmField.propagate`.

## Requirements

### R-1. §C.1 Define the curved-surface geometry record in the Domain project

This part MUST add a `CurvedSurface` record to a new file `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs` inside `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` (Part A assembly list). The record MUST carry: `radiusOfCurvature : double<meter>` (signed — negative concave, positive convex, by the sign convention fixed in C.4), `semiAperture : double<meter>` (the clear half-aperture radius), `figure : SurfaceFigure`, and `coating : OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`). All lengths MUST be stored in meters via the engine measure `[<Measure>] meter` (`Constants.fs:6`), satisfying the Part A canonical-units rule; nm/µm/mm entry MUST be converted at the UI boundary only, using `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`). The record MUST NOT introduce its own thickness or wavelength representation — thickness lives on the coating's `Layer`s (`Media.fs:12`), wavelength on the source via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`).

### R-2. §C.2 Define the `SurfaceFigure` discriminated union for spherical and aspheric profiles

This part MUST add a `SurfaceFigure` DU to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs` with exactly two cases for the committed scope: `Spherical` (curvature fully described by `CurvedSurface.radiusOfCurvature`) and `Aspheric of conic : double * evenPolynomial : double<meter> list` (conic constant plus even asphere polynomial coefficients), matching 010's "spherical/aspheric lenses" ([Core], 010 line 88). The sag function `z(r)` MUST be implemented as a pure F# function `sag : SurfaceFigure -> double<meter> -> double<meter> -> double<meter>` (figure, radius-of-curvature, radial position) returning the surface height; for `Spherical` it MUST be the exact spherical sag, for `Aspheric` the conic-plus-polynomial sag. No further figure cases (toroidal, freeform, diffractive) MAY be added — they are absent from 010 and excluded here.

### R-3. §C.3 Decompose a curved surface into local flat interfaces sampled across the aperture

This part MUST add `sampleZones : CurvedSurface -> int -> LocalZone list` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`, where the `int` is the zone count supplied by the caller and `LocalZone` is a record carrying the zone's radial position `radialPosition : double<meter>`, its `localAoiShift : Angle` (the angle between the chord normal at that radius and the optical axis, derived from `SurfaceFigure.sag` per C.2), and its `coating : OpticalSystem`. Sampling MUST be uniform in aperture radius from axis (`radialPosition = 0`) to `semiAperture`. The function MUST NOT perform adaptive refinement, MUST NOT cache, and MUST NOT default the zone count — the count is a required argument owned by the orchestration caller (Part F/G consumers of `BeamTree`). `Angle` MUST be the engine type used by `IncidenceAngle` (`Fields.fs:22`, via `Geometry.Angle`), so that C.5 can feed the shift straight into `IncidentLightInfo.rotateY` (`Fields.fs:411`).

### R-4. §C.4 Fix the signed radius-of-curvature convention for concave vs. convex elements

This part MUST document and enforce, in `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs` as an XML-doc comment on `CurvedSurface.radiusOfCurvature` and as the body of `sag` (C.2), the single sign convention: a surface whose center of curvature lies on the *incoming-light* side (concave toward the source) MUST have negative `radiusOfCurvature`, and convex MUST be positive. This is the only convention; there is NO per-element override flag and NO "convention selector" config knob. A concave mirror (`ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror`, Part A §A.4) and a convex mirror are distinguished solely by this sign. Both lens-surface curvatures of a biconvex/meniscus lens MUST be represented as two `CurvedSurface` records (one per physical surface), not as a single two-radius record, so that each surface is one local-interface evaluation.

### R-5. §C.5 Evaluate each zone through the engine 4×4 solver at its local angle of incidence

This part MUST add `solveZone : IncidentLightInfo -> LocalZone -> SolverParameters -> Solution` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`. For each `LocalZone` (C.3) it MUST: (1) form the local incident light by applying the zone's `localAoiShift` to the incoming `IncidentLightInfo` via `IncidentLightInfo.rotateY` (`Fields.fs:411`, which adds the angle onto `incidenceAngle`); (2) run the engine's per-system solver `OpticalSystemSolver(localInfo, zone.coating, parameters)` (`Solvers.fs:199`) to obtain the reflected and transmitted fields. The `SolverParameters` (`Solvers.fs:15`) MUST be passed through unchanged — the curved-element path MUST NOT invent its own reflection-count or thresholds. This part MUST NOT re-implement reflectance/transmittance; the `Solution.emSys` reflected/transmitted split (`Solvers.fs:156`) is the output, consumed downstream exactly as a flat element's output is.

### R-6. §C.6 Build the per-zone beam fan onto the Part A `BeamTree`, honoring the mirror special case

This part MUST add `attachCurvedElement : ConstructorElement -> BeamNode -> BeamNode` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`, producing, for a `Lens` or `CurvedMirror`, the fan of child `BeamNode`s (Part A §A.4) — one node per `LocalZone` solve from C.5. For `ConstructorElement.Lens` each zone node MUST expose both `BeamBranch.Reflected` and `BeamBranch.Transmitted` attachments (Part A §A.4). For `ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror` each zone node MUST expose the `BeamBranch.Reflected` attachment ONLY and MUST drop the transmitted field, matching the deliberate mirror special case (010 lines 78-80; Part A §A.4 "a mirror `BeamNode` carries the `Reflected` child ONLY"). This part MUST NOT redefine `BeamTree`, `BeamNode`, `BeamBranch`, or `ConstructorElement` — they are owned by Part A §A.4 and imported here.

### R-7. §C.7 Propagate the beam between curved elements using the engine propagator

This part MUST carry the beam from one curved element's zone output to the next element using the engine inter-element propagator `EmField.propagate (s : Layer)` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`, the seam Part A names under "Beam / field types"), wrapping the inter-element gap as a `Layer` (`Media.fs:24`) whose `thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) is the axial separation in meters and whose `properties` are the gap medium's `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`). This part MUST NOT add a second propagation routine or a ray-transfer (ABCD) matrix module; the focusing geometry needed for the committed [Core] scope is the per-zone local-AOI fan (C.3, C.5) plus this axial propagation. Full Gaussian-beam waist/divergence propagation remains the existing FFT scaffolding `createGaussian`/`FourierTransform` (`FourierTransform.fs:74,137`) and is OUT OF SCOPE for this part.

### R-8. §C.8 Attach coatings on curved surfaces as ordinary engine optical systems

This part MUST represent a coating on a curved surface as the `OpticalSystem` stored in `CurvedSurface.coating` (C.1), reusing `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`), its `films : Layer list` (`Media.fs:98`), and `Substrate` (`Plate | Wedge`, `Media.fs:40`) verbatim — the substrate material of the lens/mirror IS the coating system's `lower`/`substrate`. This part MUST NOT define a curved-specific layer or coating type. The same coating `OpticalSystem` MUST be shared by every `LocalZone` (C.3) except where C.9 rescales its layer thicknesses for grading; sharing MUST be by value (immutable record reuse), consistent with the Part A immutability commitment and CLAUDE.md immutable-structures rule.

### R-9. §C.9 Apply EUV depth-graded multilayer spacing as a per-zone thickness rescale [Core]

This part MUST add `gradeCoating : CurvedSurface -> LocalZone -> OpticalSystem` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`, which, for a depth-graded EUV multilayer mirror, returns the zone's coating with every `Layer.thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) of the bilayer stack scaled by a factor that varies with the zone's `radialPosition` (C.3) so the multilayer period changes across the aperture (~5% center-to-edge, 010 line 92, [Core]). The scaling factor MUST be computed from the zone's `localAoiShift` and applied only to `Thickness.Thickness d` cases (`Media.fs:12`), leaving `Thickness.Infinity` untouched. All scaled thicknesses MUST remain in `double<meter>` (`Constants.fs:6`); the ~5% figure is a default that MUST be expressed as a meter-valued scale, never stored in a non-SI unit (Part A canonical-units rule). Grading MUST be opt-in per element (a flag on the `ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror`/`Lens` payload, Part A §A.4); a non-graded element MUST reuse the single shared coating from C.8 with no rescale. This part MUST NOT add a new graded-layer type, a period-versus-radius config table, or schema versioning for grading.

### R-10. §C.10 Convert and validate curved-element units only at the IO/UI boundary

This part MUST keep all `CurvedSurface`/`LocalZone` fields in canonical SI (meters, engine `Angle`) inside the domain, and MUST place radius/aperture/sag unit conversion (nm/µm/mm/Å ↔ meter) in the UI/Storage layer using `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`), satisfying the Part A JSON-canonical rule. The curved-element fields added by this part MUST serialize through the JSON-canonical project model under the Part A `constructorElement` schema `$def` (Part A §A.7); they MUST NOT be FsPickler-serialized into the canonical project (Part A `.binz`-derived rule). Per-zone solver outputs, being derived bulk results, MAY be written to a `.binz` sidecar via `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize` with `BinaryZippedFormat` (`Core.fs:257`) when a sweep persists them, but this part adds no such sidecar itself.

## Non-requirements

- Redefining `BeamTree`/`BeamNode`/`BeamBranch`/`ConstructorElement` — owned by Part A §A.4 / slice 002; imported here, never redefined.
- Full 3D vector wave optics, diffraction integrals beyond the existing FFT scaffolding, or a second physics engine — Part A §A.5; the per-zone local-AOI fan is the ONLY admitted extension.
- Gaussian-beam waist/divergence propagation — remains the existing FFT scaffolding `createGaussian`/`FourierTransform` (`FourierTransform.fs:74,137`), OUT OF SCOPE per §C.7.
- A new graded-layer type, a period-versus-radius config table, or a curved-specific coating/layer type — coatings reuse `OpticalSystem`/`Layer`/`Substrate` verbatim (§C.8/§C.9).
- The UI medium/substrate/stack editor and the construction page — Part B / slice 005.
- The full schema/serializer machinery for the `constructorElement` `$def` — owned by storage (Part A §A.7 / slice 003); this part keeps fields in SI so they serialize through that model, adding no FsPickler path.
- No operator page, no long-running background job, no destructive action — §C.0 (the operator-facing UX checklist does not apply).

